{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:33:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13588"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13588"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.32,0.46,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31576"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"402"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42896"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents with a six month history of increasing fatigue and shortness of breath on exertion. He reports a long history of alcohol consumption, typically consuming several beers daily after work. Recently, he has also noticed swelling in his legs. He is currently not on any medications and has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 130/85 mmHg, pulse 88/min and respiratory rate 18/min. On cardiological assessment he has a displaced apex beat, a mild systolic murmur, jugular venous distention and bilateral pedal oedema. Laboratory findings include elevated B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) and mild liver enzyme elevations. An echocardiogram shows left ventricular dilation with a reduced ejection fraction of 35% and no significant valvular abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High-dose beta-blocker therapy immediately","Advise salt and fluid restriction","Abstinence from alcohol","Thiamine substitution","Dietary iron restriction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbstinence from alcohol\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The patient presents with symptoms typical of heart failure\u2014increasing fatigue, shortness of breath, and bilateral pedal oedema\u2014accompanied by an echocardiographic finding of left ventricular dilation and a reduced ejection fraction. These clinical features are suggestive of dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM), particularly given his significant history of alcohol consumption. Alcohol-related cardiomyopathy is a subtype of DCM where ethanol toxicity contributes to myocardial damage, leading to cardiac dilation and systolic dysfunction. Early and sustained abstinence from alcohol can lead to improvement and possibly reversal of myocardial dysfunction. Monitoring during withdrawal is critical to manage potential complications, such as arrhythmias or severe withdrawal symptoms including delirium tremens. In scenarios where alcohol is not a contributing factor, this option would be less relevant, and treatment would focus on other aetiological factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDilated cardiomyopathy (DCM) is characterised by dilation of one or both ventricles, associated with impaired systolic function, leading to heart failure with reduced ejection fraction. It can be caused by genetic factors, viral infections, toxins (including alcohol), and immune-mediated mechanisms. Management includes addressing any reversible causes, medical therapy for heart failure, and in some cases, devices or transplantation for advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-blockers \u003C/strong\u003Eare crucial in managing systolic heart failure to improve survival by reducing myocardial oxygen demand and arrhythmogenic potential. However, in the context of alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy, the primary intervention should be cessation of alcohol. Beta-blockers would not address the underlying cause and are typically not initiated in high doses immediately due to the risk of worsening heart failure symptoms or inducing bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalt and fluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is beneficial in managing symptoms related to fluid overload in heart failure, this strategy alone does not address the underlying alcohol-induced myocardial damage. It is supportive care and should be used in conjunction with addressing the primary cause and other heart failure therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiamine supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is a common and crucial treatment in patients with alcohol use disorder to prevent Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome, a serious neurologic disorder. While thiamine is essential for patients with a history of significant alcohol use to mitigate neurological risks, it does not directly address the cardiac dysfunction caused by dilated cardiomyopathy. Therefore, while important in the broader management of patients with alcohol use disorder, it is not the primary treatment for the cardiac condition described in the scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary iron restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically relevant unless there is a specific indication of iron overload, such as haemochromatosis, which is not suggested by the patient\u2019s history or presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For alcohol-induced dilated cardiomyopathy, abstinence from alcohol combined with medical therapy is crucial for reversing myocardial damage and improving cardiac function."],"references":["Tayal U, Gregson J, Buchan R, Whiffin N, Halliday BP, Lota A, Roberts AM, Baksi AJ, Voges I, Jarman JW, Baruah R. Moderate excess alcohol consumption and adverse cardiac remodelling in dilated cardiomyopathy. Heart. 2022 Apr 1;108(8):619-25.                                                           https://heart.bmj.com/content/108/8/619.abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31576"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13588"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31576"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-11T11:12:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T16:09:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46726"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"e